import Layout from '../layouts/BlogPost.astro';
---

<Layout
	title="About Me"
	description="Josh McQueen: Senior GenAI Strategist, 2x founder, builder, and human."
	pubDate={new Date('April 16 2026')}
	heroImage={AboutHeroImage}
>
	<p>
		I'm Josh McQueen. I live in San Diego, which makes it pretty easy to stay grounded: my wife, our
		dog, a beach nearby, and good weather almost every single day. That helps when you spend a lot of
		time thinking about artificial intelligence.
	</p>

	<p>
		Professionally, I've spent 15+ years in enterprise software and cloud platforms, with the last
		four years going deep on GenAI. I've co-founded two companies: <strong>Arcus Data</strong>,
		deploying big data and Splunk solutions for Fortune 100 companies, and <strong>FireFlower AI</strong>,
		a secure GenAI platform for highly regulated industries that completed a Phase I SBIR with the
		United States Air Force. I'm currently back at AWS as a Senior GenAI Strategist, helping large
		enterprises figure out how to actually deploy this technology at scale. If you want the full
		professional picture, the <a href="/">home page</a> covers it.
	</p>

	<h2>The human stuff</h2>

	<p>
		I travel as much as I can, and Italy keeps pulling me back. The food, the culture, the pace of
		life. Speaking of food: I cook seriously. I'm borderline obsessed with making the perfect pizza
		from scratch. That means proper dough, fermentation timing, and a wood-fired oven that gets to
		around 1000 degrees. When it comes together it's one of the more satisfying things I know how to
		do with my hands.
	</p>

	<p>
		I build, ride, and race motorcycles. My MotoGP team is Ducati, and I think that says something
		about how I approach most things: technically sophisticated, a little aggressive, always chasing
		the next tenth of a second.
	</p>

	<p>
		I'm wired to create. New ideas, new apps, new experiments. If something seems interesting to
		build, I'll usually just start building it. This site is partly a record of that impulse: things
		I'm working on, approaches I'm testing, stuff that didn't quite work and what I learned from it.
	</p>

	<h2>Why any of this matters</h2>

	<p>
		I spend my days working at the frontier of AI, and I genuinely believe it's one of the most
		consequential technological shifts in history. But in a world where machines are increasingly
		doing everything, I think the human element matters more, not less. Curiosity, taste, judgment,
		the willingness to try something and be wrong about it. Those things don't automate well. This
		site is my attempt to keep that thread alive.
	</p>

</Layout>
